            },
            "answer_text": "Are the character's eyes a special feature to him- or herself? Do they feature largely in his or her life story? Or, are they only \"different\" as viewed from a non-Asian perspective? The risk of \"sounding racist\" comes from viewing a minority person as The Other: homing in on their physical differences from what is assumed to be the \"norm\"taking one individual as being a representative of their entire raceMost Asians do not relate to their eye shape being a prominent part of their life history. Have you talked to a few of Asian people about their eyes, as you\u2019ve been creating this character? If the eye color and skin color are somehow integral to your character's development \u2014 then focus on events and interactions with other characters that are provoked by these salient distinctions. Pass on those all-too-familiar adjectives that come readily to mind. By the way: what is frequently assumed to be the \"Asian Eye\" isn't at all uniformly pervasive throughout Asia. In places such as Taiwan and regions of China, the much fussed-over epicanthic lid is actually in the minority. So, specifics matter. What kind of Asian are they? What is their personal identity (how they understand themselves), rather than race (which simplistic racial bucket other people stick them in)? Are they a Westerner who happens to be Asian, or a recent immigrant, or somewhere in between? That you haven't gotten more specific beyond just the top-level race label is indicative of a more important issue to tackle, than just what words you can use to tell your readers how \u201cAsian!\u201d their eyes strike other people not used to Asians. ",
