            "answer_text": "I have found this thread funny. People are asking if one \u201chas to\u201d describe eyes? Well, why ever not? Does one shy away from describing eyes other than Asian? Or are all eye-descriptions to be banned in the name of cultural-sensitivity? Please read some literature and notice when eyes are described - along with mouths, noses, hair, ears, penises and so on. Some posters try to be useful by suggesting, \u2018why not just say they are Asian\u2019 or \u2018why not just call them Yamamoto?\u2019 Huh?? Do you think calling a man \u201cMr Jones\u201d is sufficient physical description of the man in question? Do all Mr Jones\u2019s look alike to you? And then we are offered either the cliche (almond) or the scientific (monolid). Heavens, are we trying to inspire the reader or kill them? I came here because I wanted to hear how others might use language in a creative way to depict something seen and felt by a character. Obviously I don\u2019t want to use a racist generalization such as \u2018slit-eyed,\u2019 but neither do I want to use a cliche or a scientific definition. Okay, \u2018almond-shaped . . . that may be a starting point. If that is your starting point but you don\u2019t wish to use that particular cliche, ask yourself what else looks like an almond? Find other descriptors, if \u2018almond\u2019 is how you think an eye is. Or, maybe the cliche is wrong from start to finish. Preferably, deal with a description in a specific way, not through a generalization. For instance, one could write of a specific non-Asian, white character, \u201cHis eyes were heavy, weary with a lifetime of taking orders. The lids slanted down each side as if they were endlessly repeating \u201cyes sir, no sir\u201d in the manner of a somnambulist. One couldn\u2019t say what color the irises may have been for they hadn\u2019t seen the light of day for many years, maybe not for a lifetime. But the puff of the man\u2019s cheeks pushed the lower lids up in such a way that what was left, the slit which for others was the window to their soul, was, in his case, more like the ellipse of a tarnished dessert spoon, unrevealing and uninviting.\u201d (just made up this) I mean, isn\u2019t the above better than just saying, \u2018his eyes were round?\u2019 Well, it so happens that in a story I am presently writing, one character is being introduced to a young woman who has yet to discover her part-Japanese ancestry. Her eyes are introduced early on as a clue to the later revelation (important to the story line). She has not got a Japanese name but a German name (via adopted parents) and I cannot give it away yet that she is part-Japanese. I am trying to \u201cdescribe\u201d not explain. I am trying to \u201cshow\u201d not tell. Make your descriptions count. Make them \u2018sexy.\u2019 To write is to imagine and to imagine is to create. Hey, you can always try swapping pistachio for almond, if that\u2019s not too nutty. But really, are Asian eyes almond-shaped? How about \u2018swallow-tailed?\u2019 Or, is it the real problem the writer is trying to generalize, trying to find a descriptor that marks a \u2018racial\u2019 difference rather than one that marks the specificity of the particular character? Why not, instead of trying to invent a new cliche, actually find a face that suits the character you are trying to describe (google is full of photos) and then clear your mind and stare at the eyes for a long while until something comes up? Stop thinking and feel your way into it. ",
