            "author_info": {
                "name": "C.S. Friedman",
                "href": "/profile/C-S-Friedman"
            },
            "answer_text": "Jeez, guys. Are we really living in a world where describing a character\u2019s physical traits is racist? I don\u2019t agree. Yes, I did once have a writer try to convince me that it wasnot necessary to mention a character was black. In fact he insisted vehemently that the color of the character\u2019s skin did not matter, because we are not racist any more and knowing his race will not impact how one reads the story, Of course it impacts how one reads the story. your reader is picturing the character in his mind and you need to give him the basic details he needs to do that. that said, you gave the character an asian name, so you don\u2019t have to describe Asian features to make the point about what race she is. If that\u2019s the only reason you wanted to describe Asian eyes, don\u2019t. But if another character is taking note of that particular feature, and he notices her asian qualities, don\u2019t shy away from a physical description.\u201cAlmond eyes\u201d is the fallback descriptive phrase for attractive eyes of an Asian shape. as for skin color\u2026.sorry, there is no \u201cAsian\u201d skin color. There are Asians with pale, delicate coloring, with golden skin, with bronze skin, with brown skin, and every shade in between. I had two Japanese students once in a stage makeup classe who used the base for Caucasian ingenues. Decide what color you want her skin to be and describe that. The standard adjective for someone with slightly dark, slightly golden skin is \u201colive\u201d. Asian hair iis a unique texture\u2014ask any hair stylist\u2014and using the phrase \u201cAsian hair\u201d is common among my aquaintances of Asian ancestry when they want to refer to that quality. ",
