                "name": "Claire J. Vannette",
                "href": "/profile/Claire-J-Vannette"
            },
            "answer_text": "I guess you're asking about the epicanthic fold and single eyelid? A typical adjective in English-language literature is \"almond\" or \"almond-shaped.\" Which I think is extremely silly, personally: http://www.npr.org/blogs/codeswitch/2013/09/16/219402847/-almond-shaped-eyes-remarkably-exotic-yet-too-foreign. But it's an adjective many English-speaking readers will understand. Cliches have that advantage. Like other responders, I'm wondering why you need to describe this aspect of the person's eyes. Unless you have a clever way of doing it, which you obviously don't, what's the point? Describe the characteristics that are different and defining. ",
